The start symbol S can only generate a string via the rule  
S → NT33 NT20.

Therefore both NT33 and NT20 must be able to derive substrings of the given
string.

NT20 has exactly one production:  
NT20 → NT58 NT50  

Hence we must be able to derive NT58 from some part of the string.
Looking at the grammar, the only non-recursive way to obtain NT58 is

NT58 → NT1 NT30.

NT1 is the sole nonterminal that can produce the terminal t15
(NT1 → 't15').  
The given string, however, contains no occurrence of t15, so NT1 can never
appear in any derivation for this string.  Without NT1 we cannot create a
base occurrence of NT58, and consequently NT58 (and thus NT20) can never be
derived from any substring of the string.

Because NT20 cannot be generated, the start symbol S cannot generate the
whole string.

Therefore the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

NT20 must expand as NT58 NT50.  
Every derivation of NT58 ends (via NT58 → NT1 NT30) with the terminal t15 coming from NT1 → 't15'.  
Since the given string contains no occurrence of t15, NT58 cannot be part of its derivation, and therefore NT20—and consequently the start symbol S—cannot generate the string.  

No
